The Coding for All project produced new types of online tools, activities, and workshops to support the development of computational fluency among populations of youth underrepresented in the computing world. Additionally, the project identified strategies for designing online environments that are safe, positive, and inclusive, and that promote diverse interest-driven trajectories towards computational fluency.


The Berkman Klein Center for Internet and Society team, in collaboration with researchers from MIT Media Lab, and the Digital Media and Learning Hub at University of California Irvine, 




Developed and facilitated Scratch workshops for librarians and educators at various conferences and symposiums. Employing a "train-the-trainer" model, the workshops were designed to encourage formal and informal educators to explore hosting interest-based Scratch workshops;


Designed learning tools around Copyright and licensing related issues for educators, librarians, parents, and community-based digital literacy trainers; 


Designed and tested microworlds (introductory programming environments on Scratch) that are customized to particular interests of youth from diverse populations;


Studied the policies and norms of three online youth-driven platforms and communities (Scratch, Connected Camps, and DIY.org), exploring how moderation schemes and governance approaches in youth-driven online platforms can foster safe, positive, and inclusive spaces, and support diverse, interest-driven pathways to computational fluency.  




These research and design activities have resulted in the Berkman Klein Center team?s public-facing publications, directed towards both informal educators and the general public, that communicate key legal and policy issues related to young people?s online learning and participation. Moreover, our workshops informed the development of Scratch microworlds around a variety of student interests, and of learning tools for librarians and educators about Fair Use, Creative Commons, Public Domain, and other Copyright related topics. The learning tools can be used with Scratch workshops/lesson plans and are freely available on the Digital Literacy Resource Platform. These outcomes were designed to enable teachers, parents, and practitioners to easily expose more young people to science and technology, and to build bridges between STEM and other disciplines and cultures (e.g., Hip Hop). Although research on governance strategies focused on three youth-driven online educational platforms (Scratch, Connected Camps, and DIY.org), the case studies can inform the design of other learning platforms and communities, providing insights and best practices for moderation and governance, and how to foster safe, supportive, and inclusive spaces online. As the project was rooted in STEM-related learning, the work will make a significant impact on human resource development, particularly for groups of young people traditionally underrepresented in STEM fields. 

